    <h2>
      CHAPTER XI.&mdash;AN ACTRESS AT HOME
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">O</span>n a certain Monday
      in June, little more than a year after the last letter of the
      correspondence quoted in the preceding chapter, two young men of the
      period were seated in the smoking-room of the Traveller&rsquo;s Club. One was
      young George Craik, the other was Cholmondeley, of the &lsquo;Charing Cross
      Chronicle.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I assure you, my dear fellow,&rsquo; the journalist was saying, &lsquo;that if you
      are in want of a religion&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Which I am <i>not</i>,&rsquo; interjected George, sullenly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If you are in want of a new sensation, then, you will find this new
      Church just the thing to suit you. It has now been opened nearly a month,
      and is rapidly becoming the fashion. At the service yesterday I saw, among
      other notabilities, both Tyndall and Huxley, Thomas Carlyle, Hermann Vezin
      the actor, John Mill the philosopher, Dottie Destrange of the Prince&rsquo;s,
      Labouchere, and two colonial bishops. There is an article on Bradley in
      this morning&rsquo;s &ldquo;Telegraph,&rdquo; and his picture is going into next week&rsquo;s
      &ldquo;Vanity Fair.&rdquo;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But the fellow is an atheist and a Radical!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My dear Craik, so am I!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, you&rsquo;re different!&rsquo; returned the other with a disagreeable laugh.
      &lsquo;Nobody believes you in earnest when you talk or write that kind of
      nonsense.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Whereas, you would say, Bradley is an enthusiast? Just so; and his
      enthusiasm is contagious. When I listen to him, I almost catch it myself,
      for half an hour. But you mistake altogether, by the way, when you call
      him atheistical, or even Radical. He is a Churchman still, though the
      Church has banged its door in his face, and his dream is to conserve all
      that is best and strongest in Christianity.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know anything about that,&rsquo; said Craik, savagely. &lsquo;All I know is
      that he&rsquo;s an infernal humbug, and ought to be lynched.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Pray don&rsquo;t abuse him! He is my friend, and a noble fellow.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t care whether he is your friend or not&mdash;he is a scoundrel.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Cholmondeley made an angry gesture, then remembering who was speaking,
      shrugged his shoulders.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why, how has he offended <i>you</i>? Stop, though, I remember! The fair
      founder of his church is your cousin.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes,&rsquo; answered the other with an oath, &lsquo;and she would have been my wife
      if he had not come in the way. It was all arranged, you know, and I should
      have had Alma and&mdash;and all her money; but she met him, and he filled
      her mind with atheism, and radicalism, and rubbish. A year ago, when he
      was kicked out of his living, I thought she was done with him; but he
      hadn&rsquo;t been gone a month before she followed him to London, and all this
      nonsense began. The governor has almost gone down on his knees to her, but
      it&rsquo;s no use. Fancy her putting down ten thousand pounds in solid cash for
      this New Church business; and not a day passes but he swindles her out of
      more.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Bradley is not a swindler,&rsquo; answered the journalist quietly. &lsquo;For the
      rest, I suppose, that they will soon marry.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not if I can help it! Marry that man! It would be a standing disgrace to
      the family.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But they are engaged, or something of that sort. As for its being a
      disgrace, that is rubbish. Why, Bradley might marry a duke&rsquo;s daughter if
      he pleased. Little Lady Augusta Knowles is crazy about him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      True to his sarcastic instinct, Cholmondeley added, &lsquo;Of course I know the
      little woman has a hump, and has only just got over her <i>grande passion</i>
      for Montepulciano the opera singer. But a duke&rsquo;s daughter&mdash;think of
      that!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik only ground his teeth and made no reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      Shortly afterwards the two men separated, Cholmondeley strolling to his
      office, Craik (whom we shall accompany) hailing a hansom and driving
      towards St. John&rsquo;s Wood.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before seeking, in the young man&rsquo;s company, those doubtful regions which a
      modern satirist has termed
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      The shady groves of the Evangelist,
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      let us give a few explanatory words touching the subject of the above
      conversation. It had all come about exactly as described. Yielding to
      Alma&rsquo;s intercession, and inspired, moreover, by the enthusiasm of a large
      circle in London, Bradley had at last consented to open a religious
      campaign on his own account in the very heart of the metropolis. A large
      sum of money was subscribed, Alma heading the list with a princely
      donation, a site was selected in the neighbourhood of Regent&rsquo;s Park, and a
      church was built, called by its followers the New Church, and in every
      respect quite a magnificent temple. The stained windows were designed by
      leading artists of the æsthetic school, the subjects partly religious,
      partly secular (St. Wordsworth, in the guise of a good shepherd, forming
      one of the subjects, and St. Shelley, rapt up into the clouds and playing
      on a harp, forming another), and the subject over the altar was an
      extraordinary figure-piece by Watts, &lsquo;Christ rebuking Superstition&rsquo;&mdash;the
      latter a straw-haired damsel with a lunatic expression, grasping in her
      hands a couple of fiery snakes. Of course there was a scandal. The papers
      were full of it, even while the New Church was building. Public interest
      was thoroughly awakened; and when it became current gossip that a young
      heiress, of fabulous wealth and unexampled personal beauty, had
      practically created the endowment, society was fluttered through and
      through. Savage attacks appeared on Bradley in the religious journals.
      Enthusiastic articles concerning him were published in the secular
      newspapers. He rapidly became notorious. When he began to preach, the
      enthusiasm was intensified; for his striking presence and magnificent
      voice, not to speak of the &lsquo;fiery matter&rsquo; he had to deliver, carried
      everything before them.
    </p>
    <p>
      It may safely be assumed that time had at last reconciled him to the
      secret trouble of his life. Before settling in London he had ascertained,
      to his infinite relief, that Mrs. Montmorency had gone to Paris and had
      remained there with her child, under the same &lsquo;protection&rsquo; as before.
      Finding his secret safe from the world, he began unconsciously to dismiss
      it from his mind, the more rapidly as Alma&rsquo;s relations towards him became
      more and more those of a devoted sister. Presently his old enthusiasm came
      back upon him, and with it a sense of new power and mastery. He began to
      feel an unspeakable sacredness in the tie which bound him to the woman he
      loved; and although it had seemed at first that he could only think of her
      in one capacity, that of his wife and the partner of his home, her
      sisterhood seemed indescribably sweet and satisfying. Then, again, her
      extraordinary belief in him inspired him with fresh ambition, and at last,
      full of an almost youthful ardour, he stepped out into the full sunshine
      of his London ministry.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      In the least amiable mood possible, even to him, George Craik drove
      northward, and passing the very portals of Bradley&rsquo;s new church, reached
      the shady groves he sought. Alighting in a quiet street close to the &lsquo;Eyre
      Arms,&rsquo; he stood before a bijou villa all embowered in foliage, with a high
      garden wall, a gate with a wicket, and the very tiniest of green lawns. He
      rang the bell, and the gate was opened by a black-eyed girl in smart
      servant&rsquo;s costume; on which, without a word, he strolled in.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mistress up?&rsquo; he asked sharply; though it was past twelve o&rsquo;clock.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She&rsquo;s just breakfasting,&rsquo; was the reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      Crossing the lawn, Craik found himself before a pair of French windows
      reaching to the ground; they stood wide open, revealing the interior of a
      small sitting-room or breakfast parlour, gorgeously if not tastily
      furnished&mdash;a sort of green and gold cage, in which was sitting,
      sipping her coffee and yawning over a penny theatrical paper, a pretty
      lady of uncertain age. Her little figure was wrapt in a loose silk morning
      gown, on her tiny feet were Turkish slippers, in her lap was one pug dog,
      while another slept at her feet. Her eyes were very large, innocent, and
      blue, her natural dark hair was bleached to a lovely gold by the art of
      the <i>coiffeur</i>, and her cheeks had about as much colour as those of a
      stucco bust.
    </p>
    <p>
      This was Miss Dottie Destrange, of the &lsquo;Frivolity&rsquo; Theatre, a lady famous
      for her falsetto voice and her dances.
    </p>
    <p>
      On seeing Craik she merely nodded, but did not attempt to rise.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good morning, Georgie!&rsquo; she said&mdash;for she loved the diminutive, and
      was fond of using that form of address to her particular friends. &lsquo;Why
      didn&rsquo;t you come yesterday? I waited for you all day&mdash;no, not exactly
      all day, though&mdash;but except a couple of hours in the afternoon, when
      I went to church.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Craik entered the room and threw himself into a chair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Went to church?&rsquo; he echoed with an ugly laugh. 41 didn&rsquo;t know <i>you</i>
      ever patronised that kind of entertainment.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t as a rule, but Carrie Carruthers called for me in her brougham,
      and took me off to hear the new preacher down in Regent&rsquo;s Park. Aram was
      there, and no end of theatrical people, besides all sorts of swells; and,
      what do you think, in one of the painted glass windows there was a figure
      of Shakespeare, just like the one on our drop curtain! I think it&rsquo;s
      blasphemous, Georgie. I wonder the roof didn&rsquo;t fall in!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The fair doves of the theatre, we may remark in parenthesis, have seldom
      much respect for the temple in which they themselves flutter; they cannot
      shake from their minds the idea that it is a heathen structure, and that
      they themselves are, at the best, but pretty pagans.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hence they are often disposed to receive in quite a humble spirit the
      ministrations of their mortal enemies, the officers of the Protestant
      Church.
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik scowled at the fair one as he had scowled at Oholmondeley.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You heard that man Bradley, I suppose?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes; I think that was his name. Do you know him, George?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I know no good of him. I wish the roof <i>had</i> fallen in, and smashed
      him up. Talk about something else; and look here, don&rsquo;t let me catch you
      going there again, or we shall quarrel. I won&rsquo;t have any one I know going
      sneaking after that humbug.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;All right, Georgie dear,&rsquo; replied the damsel, smiling maliciously. &lsquo;Then
      it&rsquo;s true, I suppose, that he&rsquo;s going to marry your cousin? I saw her
      sitting right under him, and thought her awfully pretty.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You let her alone,&rsquo; grumbled George, &lsquo;and mind your own affairs.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why don&rsquo;t you marry her yourself, Géorgie?&rsquo; persisted his tormentor. &lsquo;I
      hope what I have heard isn&rsquo;t true?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What have you heard?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That she prefers the parson!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The young man sprang up with an oath, and Miss Dottie burst into a peal of
      shrill laughter. He strode off into the garden, and she followed him.
      Coming into the full sunlight, she looked even more like plaster of Paris,
      or stucco, than in the subdued light of the chamber; her hair grew more
      strawlike, her eyes more colourless, her whole appearance more faded and
      jaded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I had a letter this morning from Kitty,&rsquo; she said carelessly, to change
      the subject.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Kitty who?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Kitty Montmorency. She says old Ombermere is very ill, and thinks he&rsquo;s
      breaking up. By the way, that reminds me&mdash;Kitty&rsquo;s first husband was a
      man named Bradley, who was to have entered the Church. I suppose it can&rsquo;t
      be the same.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She spoke with little thought of the consequences, and was not prepared
      for the change which suddenly came over her companion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Her <i>husband</i>, did you say?&rsquo; he exclaimed, gripping her arm. &lsquo;Were
      they married?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I suppose so.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And the man was named Bradley&mdash;Ambrose Bradley?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m not <i>quite</i> sure about the Christian name.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;How long was this ago?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, a long time&mdash;ten years,&rsquo; she replied; then with a sudden
      remembrance of her own claims to juvenility, which she had forgotten for a
      moment, she added, &lsquo;when I was quite a child.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik looked at her for a long time with a baleful expression, but
      he scarcely saw her, being lost in thought. He knew as well as she did
      that she was ten or fifteen years older than she gave herself out to be,
      but he was not thinking of that. He was wondering if he had, by the merest
      accident, discovered a means of turning the tables on the man he hated. At
      last he spoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Tell me all you know. Let us have no humbug, but tell me everything. Did
      you ever see Bradley before you saw him yesterday?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Never, Georgie.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But Kitty Montmorency was once married to, or living with, a man of that
      name? You are quite sure?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes. But after all, what does it signify, unless&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She paused suddenly, for all at once the full significance of the
      situation flashed upon her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You see how it stands,&rsquo; cried her companion. &lsquo;If this is the same man,
      and it is quite possible, it will be worth a thousand pounds to me&mdash;ah,
      ten thousand! What is Kitty&rsquo;s address?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hôtel de la Grande Bretagne, Rue Caumartin, Paris.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      All right, Hottie. I shall go over to-night by the mail.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The next morning George Craik arrived in Paris, and drove straight to the
      hotel in the Rue Caumartin&mdash;an old-fashioned building, with a great
      courtyard, round which ran open-air galleries communicating with the
      various suites of rooms. On inquiring for Mrs. Montmorency he ascertained
      that she had gone out very early, and was not expected home till midday.
      He left his card and drove on to the Grand Hotel.
    </p>
    <p>
      It might be a fool&rsquo;s errand which had brought him over, but he was
      determined, with the bulldog tenacity of his nature, to see it through to
      the end.
    </p>
    <p>
      Arrived at the hotel, he deposited his Gladstone-bag in the hall, and
      then, to pass the time, inspected the visitors&rsquo; list, preparatory to
      writing down his own name.
    </p>
    <p>
      Presently he uttered a whistle, as he came to the entry&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Lord and Lady Ombermere and family, London.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He turned to the clerk of the office, and said carelessly in French&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I see Lord Ombermere&rsquo;s name down. Is his lordship still here?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes,&rsquo; was the reply. &lsquo;He has been here all the winter. Unfortunately,
      since the warm weather began, milord has been very ill, and since last
      week he has been almost given up by the physicians.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0002" id="link2HCH0002"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XII&mdash;IN A SICK ROOM.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      All blessed promise! Shall it be fulfilled,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Tho&rsquo; the eye glazes and the sense is still&rsquo;d?
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Shall that fair Shape which beckon&rsquo;d with bright hand
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Out of the Mirage of a Heavenly Land,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Fade to a cloud that moves with blighting breath
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Over the ever-troublous sea of Death?
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Ah no; for on the crown of Zion&rsquo;s Hill,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Cloth&rsquo;d on with peace, the fair Shape beckons still!
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      The New Crusade.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">I</span>t was a curious
      sensation for Ambrose Bradley, after bitter experience of a somewhat
      ignominious persecution, to find himself all at once&mdash;by a mere
      shuffle of the cards, as it were&mdash;one of the most popular persons in
      all Bohemia; I say Bohemia advisedly, for of course that greater world of
      fashion and religion, which Bohemia merely fringes, regarded the New
      Church and its pastor with supreme indifference.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the worship of Bohemia is something; nay, Bradley found it much.
    </p>
    <p>
      He could count among the occasional visitors to his temple some of the
      leading names in Art and Science. Fair votaries came to him by legions,
      led by the impassioned and enthusiastic Alma Craik. The society journals
      made much of him; one of them, in a series of articles called &lsquo;Celebrities
      in their Slippers,&rsquo; gave a glowing picture of the new Apostle in his
      study, in which the sweetest of Raphael&rsquo;s Madonnas looked down wonderingly
      on Milo&rsquo;s Venus, and where Newman&rsquo;s &lsquo;Parochial Sermons&rsquo; stood side by side
      with Tyndall&rsquo;s Belfast address, and the original edition of the &lsquo;Vestiges
      of Creation.&rsquo; The correspondent of the &lsquo;New York Herald&rsquo; telegraphed, on
      more than one occasion, the whole, or nearly the whole, of one of his
      Sunday discourses&mdash;which, printed in large type, occupied two columns
      of the great Transatlantic daily; and he received forthwith, from an
      enterprising Yankee caterer, an offer of any number of dollars per
      lecture, if he would enter into a contract to &lsquo;stump&rsquo; the States.
    </p>
    <p>
      Surely this was fame, of a sort.
    </p>
    <p>
      Although, if the truth must be told, even Bohemia did not take the New
      Church overseriously, Bradley found his intellectual forces expand with
      the growing sense of power.
    </p>
    <p>
      Standing in no fear of any authority, human or superhuman, he gradually
      advanced more and more into the arena of spiritual controversy; retired
      further and further from the old landmarks of dogmatic religion; drew
      nearer and still nearer to the position of an accredited teacher of
      religious æstheticism. Always literary and artistic, rather than
      puritanical, in his sympathies, he found himself before long at that
      standpoint which regards the Bible merely as a poetical masterpiece, and
      accepts Christianity as simply one manifestation, though a central one, of
      the great scheme of human morals.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus the cloud of splendid supernaturalism, on which alone has been
      projected from time immemorial the mirage of a heavenly promise, gradually
      dissolved away before his sight,
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And like the cloudy fabric of a vision
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Left not a wrack behind.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      The creed of spiritual sorrow was exchanged for the creed of spiritual
      pleasure. The man, forgetful of all harsh experience, became rapt in the
      contemplation of &lsquo;beautiful ideas&rsquo;&mdash;of an intellectual phantasmagoria
      in which Christ and Buddha, St. John and Shakespeare, Mary Magdalene and
      Mary Shelley, the angels of the church and the winged pterodactyls of the
      chalk, flashed and faded in everchanging kaleidoscopic dream.
    </p>
    <p>
      The mood which welcomed all forms of belief, embraced none utterly, but
      contemplated all, became vague, chaotic, and transcendental; and Ambrose
      Bradley found himself in a fairy world where nothing seemed real and
      solemn enough as a law for life.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a time, of course, he failed to realise his own position.
    </p>
    <p>
      He still rejoiced in the belief that he was building the foundation of his
      New Church, which was essentially the Old Church, on the rock of common
      sense. He was still certain that the Christ of history, the accredited
      Saviour of mankind, was blessing and consecrating his eager endeavour. He
      still persuaded himself that his creed was a creed of regeneration, his
      mission apostolic.
    </p>
    <p>
      He had taken a small house on the borders of Regent&rsquo;s Park, and not far
      away from the church which Alma had built for him as a voluntary offering.
      It was arranged plainly but comfortably, with a touch of the then
      predominant æstheticism; the decorations tasteful, the furniture
      mediaeval; but all this was Alma&rsquo;s doing and, throughout, her choosing.
      Bradley himself remained unchanged; a strong unpretending man of simple
      habits, more like an athletic curate in his dress and bearing than like a
      fashionable preacher.
    </p>
    <p>
      Of course it goes without saying that he was ostracised by the preachers
      of his own maternal Church, the Church of England; so that he added the
      consciousness of sweet and painless martyrdom to that of popular success
      Attacks upon him appeared from time to time in the less important
      religious journals; but the great organs of the national creed treated him
      and his performances with silent contempt.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was seated in his study one morning in early summer, reading one of the
      attacks to which I have just alluded, when Miss Craik was shown in. He
      sprang up to welcome her, with outstretched hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I want you to come with me at once,&rsquo; she said. &lsquo;Agatha Combe is worse,
      and I should like you to see her.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Of course I will come,&rsquo; answered Bradley.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But I thought she was almost recovered?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She has had a relapse; not a serious one, I trust, but I am a little
      alarmed about her. She talks so curiously.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Indeed!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes; about dying. She says she has a presentiment that she won&rsquo;t live.
      Poor Agatha! When <i>she</i> talks like that, it is strange indeed.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Leaving the house together, Bradley and Alma entered Regent&rsquo;s Park. Their
      way lay right across, towards the shady sides of Primrose Hill, where Miss
      Combe was then residing. The day was fair and sunny, and there was an
      unusual number of pleasure-seekers and pedestrians in the park. A number
      of boys were playing cricket on the spaces allotted for that recreation,
      nursemaids and children were sprinkled everywhere, and near the gate of
      the Zoological Gardens, which they passed, a brass band was merrily
      performing. Bradley&rsquo;s heart was light, and he looked round on the bright
      scene with a kindling eye, in the full pride of his physical strength and
      intellectual vigour.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;After all,&rsquo; he said, &lsquo;those teachers are wise who proclaim that health is
      happiness. What a joyful world it would be if everyone were well and
      strong.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ah yes!&rsquo; said his companion. &lsquo;But when sickness comes&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She sighed heavily, for she was thinking of her friend Agatha Combe.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I sometimes think that the sum of human misery is trifling compared to
      that of human happiness,&rsquo; pursued the clergyman. &lsquo;Unless one is a
      downright pessimist, a very Schopenhauer, surely one must see that the
      preponderance is in favour of enjoyment. Look at these ragged boys&mdash;how
      merry they are! There is not so much wretchedness in the world, perhaps,
      as some of us imagine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She glanced at him curiously, uncertain whither his thoughts were tending.
      He speedily made his meaning plain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Religion and Sorrow have hitherto gone hand in hand, vanishing through
      the gate of the grave. But why should not Religion and Joy be united this
      side the last mystery? Why should not this world be the Paradise of all
      our dreams?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It can never be so, Ambrose,&rsquo; replied Alma, &lsquo;until we can abolish Death.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And we can do that in a measure; that is to say, we can abolish premature
      decay, sick ness, disease. Look what Science has done in fifty years! More
      than other-worldliness has done in a thousand! When Death comes gently, at
      the natural end of life, it generally comes as a blessing&mdash;as the
      last sacrament of peace. I think if I could live man&rsquo;s allotted term,
      useful, happy, loving and beloved, I could be content to sleep and never
      wake again.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Alma did not answer. Her thoughts were wandering, or she would have shrunk
      to find her idolised teacher turning so ominously towards materialism. But
      indeed it was not the first time that Bradley&rsquo;s thoughts had drifted in
      that direction. It is not in moments of personal happiness or success that
      we lean with any eagerness towards the supernatural. Glimpses of a world
      to come are vouchsafed chiefly to those who weep and those who fail; and
      in proportion as the radiance of this life brightens, fades the faint
      aurora of the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      In a small cottage, not far from Chalk Farm, they found Miss Combe. She
      was staying, as her custom was, with friends, the friends on this occasion
      being the editor of an evening paper and his wife; and she had scarcely
      arrived on her visit&mdash;some weeks before&mdash;when she had begun to
      ail. She was sitting up when Alma arrived, in an armchair drawn close to
      the window of a little back parlour, commanding a distant view of
      Hampstead Hill.
    </p>
    <p>
      Wrapt in a loose dressing-gown, and leaning back in her chair, she was
      just touched by the spring sunshine, the brightness of which even the
      smoke from the great city could not subdue. She did not seem to be in
      pain, but her face was pale and flaccid, her eyes were heavy and dull. Her
      ailment was a weakness of the heart&rsquo;s action, complicated with internal
      malady of another kind.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tears stood in Alma&rsquo;s eyes as she embraced and kissed her old friend.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I have brought Mr. Bradley to see you,&rsquo; she cried. &lsquo;I am glad to see you
      looking so much better.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Miss Combe smiled and held out her hand to Bradley, who took it gently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;When you came in,&rsquo; she said, &lsquo;I was half dreaming. I thought I was a
      little child again, playing with brother Tom in the old churchyard at
      Taviton. Tom has only just gone out; he has been here all the morning.&rsquo;
      Said brother Tom, the unwashed apostle of the Hall of Science, had left
      unmistakable traces of his presence, for a strong odour of bad tobacco
      pervaded the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It seems like old times,&rsquo; proceeded the little lady, with a sad smile,
      &lsquo;to be sick, and to be visited by a clergyman. I shall die in the odour of
      sanctity after all.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You must not talk of dying,&rsquo; cried Alma.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You will soon be all right again.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m afraid not, dear,&rsquo; answered Miss Combe. &lsquo;I saw my mother&rsquo;s face again
      last night, and it never stayed so long. I take it as a warning that I
      shall soon be called away.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Strange enough it seemed to both those who listened, to hear a person of
      Miss Combe&rsquo;s advanced views talking in the vocabulary of commonplace
      superstition.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t think I am repining,&rsquo; she continued. &lsquo;If I were not ripe, do you
      think I should be gathered? I am going where we all must go&mdash;who
      knows whither? and, after all, I&rsquo;ve had a &ldquo;good time,&rdquo; as the Yankees say.
      Do you believe, Mr. Bradley,&rsquo; she added, turning her keen, grave eyes on
      the clergyman, &lsquo;that an atheist can be a spiritualist, and hold relations
      with an unseen world?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You are no atheist, Miss Combe,&rsquo; he answered. &lsquo;God forbid!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know,&rsquo; was the reply. &lsquo;I am not one in the same degree as my
      brother Tom of course; but I am afraid I have no living faith beyond the
      region of ghosts and fairies. The idea of Deity is incomprehensible to me,
      save as that of the &ldquo;magnified non-natural Man&rdquo; my teachers have long ago
      discarded. I think I might still understand the anthropomorphic God of my
      childhood, but having lost Him I can comprehend no other.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The other is not far to seek,&rsquo; responded Bradley, bending towards her,
      and speaking eagerly. &lsquo;You will find him in Jesus Christ&mdash;the living,
      breathing godhead, whose touch and inspiration we all can feel.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m afraid <i>I</i> can&rsquo;t,&rsquo; said Miss Combe. &lsquo;I can understand Jesus the
      man, but Christ the God, who walked in the flesh and was crucified, is
      beyond the horizon of my conception&mdash;even of my sympathy.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t say that,&rsquo; cried Alma. &lsquo;I am sure you believe in our loving
      Saviour.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Miss Combe did not reply, but turned her face wearily to the spring
      sunlight.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If there is no other life,&rsquo; she said, after a long pause, &lsquo;the idea of
      Jesus Christ is a mockery. Don&rsquo;t you think so, Mr. Bradley?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not altogether,&rsquo; replied Bradley, after a moment&rsquo;s hesitation. &lsquo;If the
      life we live here were all, if, after a season, we vanished like the
      flowers, we should still need the comfort of Christ&rsquo;s message&mdash;his
      injunction to &ldquo;love one another.&rdquo; The central idea of Christianity is
      peace and good fellowship; and if our life had raised itself to that ideal
      of love, it would be an ideal life, and its brevity would be of little
      consequence.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Miss Combe smiled. Her keen intelligence went right into the speaker&rsquo;s
      mind, and saw the true meaning of that shallow optimism. Bradley noticed
      the smile, and coloured slightly under the calm, penetrating gaze of the
      little woman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I have always been taught to believe,&rsquo; said Miss Combe, quietly, &lsquo;that
      the true secret of the success of Christianity was its heavenly promise&mdash;its
      pledge of a future life.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Of course,&rsquo; cried Alma.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Certainly that promise was given,&rsquo; said Bradley, &lsquo;and I have no doubt
      that, in some way or another, it will be fulfilled.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What do you mean by in some way or another?&rsquo; asked Miss Combe.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I mean that Christ&rsquo;s Heaven may not be a heaven of physical
      consciousness, but of painless and passive perfection; bringing to the
      weary peace and forgetfulness, to the happy absolute absorption into the
      eternal and unconscious life of God.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Nirwâna, in short!&rsquo; said Miss Combe, dryly. &lsquo;Well, for my own part, I
      should not care so much for so sleepy a Paradise. I postulate a heaven
      where I should meet and know my mother, and where the happy cry of living
      creatures would rise like a fountain into the clear azure for evermore.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Surely,&rsquo; said Bradley, gently, &lsquo;we all hope as much!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But do we <i>believe</i> it?&rsquo; returned Miss Combe. &lsquo;That is the question.
      All human experience, all physiology, all true psychology, is against it.
      The letter of the eternal Universe, written on the open Book of Astronomy,
      speaks of eternal death and change. Shall we survive while systems perish,
      while suns go out like sparks, and the void is sown with the wrecks of
      worn-out worlds?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      In this strain the conversation continued for some little time longer.
      Seeing the invalid&rsquo;s tender yearning, Bradley spoke yet more hopefully of
      the great Christian promise, describing the soul as imperishable, and the
      moral order of the universe as stationary and secure; but what he said was
      half-hearted, and carried with it no conviction. He felt for the first
      time the helplessness of a transcendental Christianity, like his own.
      Presently he returned, almost unconsciously, to the point from which he
      had set forth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;There is something, perhaps,&rsquo; he said, &lsquo;in the Positivist conception of
      mankind as one ever-changing and practically deathless Being. Though men
      perish, Man survives. Children spring like flowers in the dark footprints
      of Death, and in them the dead inherit the world.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That creed would possibly suit me,&rsquo; retimed Miss Combe, smiling sadly
      again, &lsquo;if I were a mother, if I were to live again in my own offspring.
      I&rsquo;m afraid it is a creed with little comfort for childless men, or for old
      maids like myself! No; my selfishness requires something much more
      tangible. If I am frankly told that I must die, that consciousness ceases
      for ever with the physical breath of life, I can understand it, and accept
      my doom; it is disagreeable, since I am rather fond of life and activity,
      but I can accept it. It is no consolation whatever to reflect that I am to
      exist vicariously, without consciousness of the fact, in other old maids
      to come! The condition of moral existence is&mdash;consciousness; without
      <i>that</i>, I shall be practically abolished. Such a creed, as the other
      you have named, is simple materialism, disguise it as you will.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am not preaching Positivism,&rsquo; cried Bradley; &lsquo;God forbid! I only said
      there was something in its central idea. Christ&rsquo;s promise is that we shall
      live again! Can we not accept that promise, without asking &ldquo;how?&rdquo;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, we can&rsquo;t; that is to say, <i>I</i> can&rsquo;t. It is the &ldquo;how&rdquo; which forms
      the puzzle. Besides, the Bible expressly speaks of the resurrection of the
      body.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A poetical expression,&rsquo; suggested Bradley.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes; but something more,&rsquo; persisted the little woman. &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t conceive
      an existence without those physical attributes with which I was born. When
      I think of my dead mother, it is of the very face and form I used to know;
      the same eyes, the same sweet lips, the same smile, the same touch of
      loving hands. Either we shall exist again <i>as we are</i>, or&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Of course we shall so exist,&rsquo; broke in Alma, more and more nervous at the
      turn the conversation was taking. &lsquo;Is it not all beautifully expressed in
      St. Paul? We sow a physical body, we shall reap a spiritual body; but they
      will be one and the same. But pray do not talk of it any more. You are not
      dying, dear, thank God!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Half an hour later Bradley and Alma left the house together.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am sorry dear Agatha has not more faith,&rsquo; said Alma, thoughtfully, as
      they wandered back towards the park.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I think she has a great deal,&rsquo; said Bradley, quickly. &lsquo;But I was shocked
      to see her looking so ill and worn. Is she having good medical advice?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The best in London. Dr. Harley sees her nearly every day. Poor Agatha!
      She has not had too much happiness in this world. She has worked so hard,
      and all alone!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      They entered the park gate, and came again among the greenness and the
      sunshine. Everything seemed light and happiness, and the air had that
      indescribable sense of resurrection in it which comes with the early
      shining of the primrose and the reawakening of the year. Bradley glanced
      at his companion. Never had she seemed so bright and beautiful!
    </p>
    <p>
      With the flush of the rose on her cheek, and her eyes full of pensive
      light, she moved lightly and gracefully at his side.
    </p>
    <p>
      A lark rose from the grass not far away, and warbled ecstatically
      overhead. Bradley felt his blood stir and move like sap in the bough at
      the magic touch of the season, and with kindling eyes he drew nearer to
      his companion&rsquo;s side.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, dearest, you were a true prophet,&rsquo; he said, taking her hand and
      drawing it softly within his arm. &lsquo;It has all come to pass, through <i>you</i>.
      The New Church flourishes in spite of those who hate all things new; and I
      have you&mdash;you only&mdash;to thank for it all.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I want no thanks,&rsquo; replied Alma. &lsquo;It is reward enough to forward the good
      work, and to make you happy.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Happy? Yes, I ought to be happy, should I not?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And you are, I hope, dear Ambrose!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, I think so. Only sometimes&mdash;on a day like this, for example&mdash;I
      cannot help looking back with a sigh to the dear old times at Fensea. A
      benediction seems to rest upon the quiet country life, which contented me
      <i>then</i> so little. I miss the peaceful fields, the loneliness and rest
      of the fens, the silence of the encircling sea!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And Goody Tilbury&rsquo;s red cloak!&rsquo; cried Alma, smiling. &lsquo;And the scowl of
      Summerhayes the grocer, and the good. Bishop&rsquo;s blessing!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ah, but after all the life was a gentle one till I destroyed it. The poor
      souls loved me, till I became too much for them. And then, Alma, the days
      with <i>you</i>! Your first coming, like a ministering angel, to make this
      sordid earth seem like a heavenly dream! To-day, dearest, it almost seems
      as if my heaven was behind, and not before, me! I should like to live
      those blissful moments over again&mdash;every one!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Alma laughed outright, for she had a vivid remembrance of her friend&rsquo;s
      infinite vexations as a country clergyman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s right,&rsquo; he said, smiling fondly; &lsquo;laugh at me, if you please, but
      I am quite serious in what I say. Here, in the great world of London,
      though we see so much of one another, we do not seem quite so closely
      united as we did yonder.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not so united!&rsquo; she cried, all her sweet face clouded in a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, united as before, but differently. In the constant storm and stress
      of my occupation, there is not the same pastoral consecration.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      The world is too much with us; late and soon,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Getting and spending, we lay waste our powers.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      In those days, dearest,&rsquo; he added, sinking his voice to a whisper, &lsquo;we
      used to speak oftener of love, we used to dream&mdash;did we not?&mdash;of
      being man and wife.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She drooped her gentle eyes, which had been fixed upon him earnestly, and
      coloured softly; then, with a pretty touch of coquetry, laughed again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am not jealous,&rsquo; she said, &lsquo;and since you have another bride&mdash;-&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Another bride!&rsquo; he repeated, with a startled look of surprise.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I mean your Church,&rsquo; she said gaily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ah yes,&rsquo; he said, relieved. &lsquo;But do you know I find this same bride of
      mine a somewhat dull companion, and a poor exchange, at any rate, for a
      bride of flesh and blood. Dearest, I have been thinking it all over! Why
      should we not realise our old dream, and live in love together?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Alma stood silent. They were in a lonely part of the park, in a footway
      winding through its very centre. Close at hand was one of the wooden
      benches. With beating heart and heightened colour, she strolled to the
      seat and sat down.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley followed, placed himself by her side, and gently took her hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well?&rsquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      She turned her head and looked quietly into his eyes. Her grave fond look
      brought the bright blood to his own cheeks, and just glancing round to see
      that they were unobserved, he caught her in his arms and kissed her
      passionately&mdash;on lips that kissed again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Shall it be as I wish?&rsquo; he exclaimed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, Ambrose,&rsquo; she answered. &lsquo;What you wish, I wish too; now as always,
      your will is my law.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And when?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;When you please,&rsquo; she answered. &lsquo;Only before I marry you, you must
      promise me one thing.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes! yes!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To regard me <i>still</i> as only your handmaid; to look upon your Church
      always as your true Bride, to whom you are most deeply bound.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll try, dear; but will you be very angry if I sometimes forget her,
      when I feel your loving arms around me?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Very angry,&rsquo; she said, smiling radiantly, upon him.
    </p>
    <p>
      They rose up, and walked on together hand in hand.
    </p>
    <p>
