    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XIV.&mdash;A MYSTERY.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">B</span>radley and his
      bride were only absent from London five days; no one missed them, and of
      course no one suspected that they had gone away in company. Before the
      next Sunday came round, they were living just as before&mdash;she in her
      own rooms, he in the residence at Regent&rsquo;s Park. This was the arrangement
      made between them, the clergyman&rsquo;s plea being that it was better to keep
      their marriage secret for a time, until the New Church was more safely
      established in public estimation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Quite happy in the loving secret between them, Alma had acquiesced without
      a word.
    </p>
    <p>
      Their only confidant, for the time being, was Miss Combe, who was then
      staying at Hastings, and to whom Alma wrote in the following terms:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Dearest Agatha,&mdash;It is all over, and we are man and wife. No one in
      the world is to know but <i>you</i>, yet awhile. I know you will keep our
      secret, and rejoice in our happiness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It was all decided very hastily. Ambrose thought it better to marry
      secretly, thinking (foolish man!) that many would misunderstand his
      motives, and believing that, as an unmarried person, he can better pursue
      the good work to which we are both devoted. After all, it matters very
      little. For years we have been one in soul, as you know; and what God long
      ago joined man could never have put asunder. Still, it is sweet to know
      that my hero, my apostle, my Abelard&mdash;as I call him, is entirely
      mine, for richer, for poorer, for better, for worse. I am very happy,
      dear; proud and hopeful, too, as a loving wife can be.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Write and tell me that you are better. Surely this bright weather should
      complete your cure, and drive those gloomy thoughts away? In a few days I
      shall come and see you; perhaps we may come together. So I won&rsquo;t write
      good bye, but <i>au revoir!</i>
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Your loving friend,
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Alma Bradley.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;P.S.&mdash;My cousin George is back in town. Just fancy how he would
      scowl if he were to read the above <i>signature.</i>&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      It so happened that George Craik, although he was not so favoured as to
      read his cousin&rsquo;s signature as a married woman, and although he had no
      suspicion whatever as yet that she had entered, as she imagined, into the
      holy estate of matrimony, was scowling in his least amiable frame of mind
      about the time when Alma wrote the above letter. He had returned to London
      from Paris a good deal mystified, for, having procured an interview with
      Mrs. Montmorency, whom (as the reader knows) he had gone over to see, he
      had elicited nothing from that lady but a flat denial of any knowledge of
      or connection with his rival the clergyman.
    </p>
    <p>
      So he came back at once, baffled but not beaten, took to the old club
      life, attended the different race meetings, and resumed altogether the
      life of a young gentleman about town.
    </p>
    <p>
      But although he saw little of his cousin, he (as he himself figuratively
      expressed it &lsquo;kept his eye upon her.&rsquo;) The more he read about Bradley and
      his doings&mdash;which appeared shocking indeed to his unsophisticated
      mind&mdash;the more indignant he felt that Alma, and her fortune, should
      ever be thrown away on one so unworthy. Meantime he was in the unenviable
      position of a man surrounded by duns and debts. He had bills out in the
      hands of the Jews, and he saw no prospect whatever of meeting them. Having
      far exceeded the very liberal allowance given him by his father, he knew
      that there was no hope of assistance in that direction. His only chance of
      social resuscitation was a wealthy marriage, and with his cousin hanging
      like a tempting bait before him, he felt like a very Tantalus, miserable,
      indignant and ill-used.
    </p>
    <p>
      His rooms were in the Albany, and here one morning his father found him,
      sitting over a late breakfast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, George,&rsquo; said the baronet, standing on the hearthrug and glancing
      round at the highly suggestive prints which adorned the walls; &lsquo;well,
      George, how long is this to last?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The young man glanced up gloomily as he sipt his coffee.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What do you mean?&rsquo; he demanded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You know very well. But just look at this letter, which I have received,
      from a man called Tavistock, this morning.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      And he tossed it over the table to his son. George took it up, looked at
      it, and flushed crimson. It was a letter informing Sir George Craik that
      the writer held in his hands a dishonoured acceptance of his son&rsquo;s for the
      sum of three hundred pounds, and that unless it was taken up within a week
      proceedings in bankruptcy would be instituted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;D&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; the Jew!&rsquo; cried George. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll wring his neck! He
      had no right to write to you!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I suppose he thought it was the only way,&rsquo; returned the baronet; &lsquo;but he
      is quite out in his calculations. If you suppose that I shall pay any more
      of your debts you are mistaken. I am quite tired of it all. You have
      played all your cards wrong and must take the consequences.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George scowled more furiously than ever, but made no immediate reply.
      After a pause, however, he said in an injured way&mdash;&lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know what
      you mean by playing my cards wrong. I have done my best. If my cousin Alma
      has given me the cold shoulder, because she has gone cranky on religion,
      it is no fault of mine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am not astonished that she has thrown you over,&rsquo; cried Sir George.
      &lsquo;What possible interest could a young girl of her disposition find in a
      fellow who bets away his last shilling, and covers his room with pictures
      of horses and portraits of jockeys and ballet girls? If you had had any
      common sense, you might at least have pretended to take some interest in
      her pursuits.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m not a hypocrite,&rsquo; retorted George, &lsquo;and I can&rsquo;t talk atheism.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Rubbish! You know as well as I do that Alma is a high-spirited girl, and
      only wants humouring. These new-fangled ideas of hers are absurd enough,
      but irritating opposition will never lead her to get rid of them.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She&rsquo;s in love with that fellow Bradley!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Nothing of the kind. She is in love with her own wild fancies, which he
      is wise enough to humour, and you are indiscreet enough to oppose. If
      there had been anything serious between them, a marriage would have come
      off long ago; but, absurd as Alma is, she is not mad enough to throw
      herself away on a mere adventurer like that, without a penny in the
      world.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What is a fellow to do?&rsquo; pleaded George, dolefully. &lsquo;She snubs me more
      than ever!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The more she snubs you the more you ought to pursue her. Show your
      devotion to her&mdash;go to the church&mdash;seem to be interested in her
      crotchets&mdash;and take my word for it, her sympathies will soon turn in
      your direction.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Father and son continued to talk for some time in the same strain, and
      after an hour&rsquo;s conversation Sir George went away in a better humour.
      George drest himself carefully, and when it was about midday hailed a cab
      and was driven down to the Gaiety Theatre, where he had an appointment
      with Miss Dottie Destrange. The occasion was one of those <i>matinées</i>
      when aspiring amateurs attempt to take critical opinion by storm, and the
      <i>débutante</i> this time was a certain Mrs. Temple Grainger, who was to
      appear as &lsquo;Juliet&rsquo; in the <i>Hunchback</i>, and afterwards as &lsquo;Juliet&rsquo; in
      the famous balcony scene of Shakespeare&rsquo;s play. Mrs. Grainger, whose
      husband was somewhere in the mysterious limbo of mysterious husbands,
      called India, was well known in a certain section of society, and no less
      a person than His Royal Highness the Prince of Wales had promised to be
      present at her <i>début</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      George was to join Miss Destrange in the stalls, where he duly found her,
      and was greeted with a careless smile. The seats all round were thronged
      with well-known members of society; actresses, actors, critics. The Prince
      was already in his box, and the curtain was just ringing up.
    </p>
    <p>
      It is no part of my business to chronicle the success or failure of Mrs.
      Temple Grainger; but, if cheers and floral offerings signify anything, she
      was in high favour with her audience. At the end of the second act, George
      Craik rose and surveyed the house through his opera glass. As he did so,
      he was conscious of a figure saluting him from one of the stage boxes, and
      to his surprise he recognised&mdash;Mrs. Montmorency.
    </p>
    <p>
      She was gorgeously drest in black, and liberally painted and powdered.
      George bowed to her carelessly; when to his surprise she beckoned him to
      her.
    </p>
    <p>
      He rose from his seat and walked over to the side of the stalls
      immediately underneath her box. She leant over to him, and they shook
      hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Will you come in?&rsquo; she said. &lsquo;I want to speak to you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He nodded, passed round to the back of the box, entered, and took a seat
      by the lady&rsquo;s side.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I thought you were still in Paris,&rsquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I came over about a fortnight ago,&rsquo; she replied. &lsquo;I suppose you have
      heard of his lordship&rsquo;s death?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes. I saw it in the papers.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I waited till after the funeral, then I came away. But we won&rsquo;t talk
      about that; I&rsquo;ve hardly got over it yet. I&rsquo;ve something else to say to
      you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do you remember a question you asked me in Paris&mdash;whether I knew
      anything of a clergyman of the name of Bradley who was paying his
      addresses to your cousin?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Of course I do; and you said&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That I only knew him very slightly.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Pardon me, but you said you didn&rsquo;t know him at all!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Did I? Then I made a slight mistake.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I do know the person you mean by sight!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik looked at the speaker with some astonishment, for he had a
      good memory, and a very vivid recollection of what she had said to him
      during their interview.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I dare say I was <i>distrait</i>,&rsquo; she continued, with a curious smile
      and a flash of her dark eyes. &lsquo;I was in such trouble about poor Ombermere.
      What I want to tell you is that I saw Mr. Bradley the other day at Rouen,
      as I was returning from Paris.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;At Rouen,&rsquo; repeated George Craik.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, on the railway platform, in company with a very charming lady, who
      was hanging on his arm, and regarding him with very evident adoration.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George pricked up his ears like a little terrier; he smelt mischief of
      some sort.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I fancy you must be mistaken,&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;Bradley is not likely to have
      been travelling across the Channel.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am not at all mistaken,&rsquo; answered Mrs. Montmorency. &lsquo;Mr. Bradley&rsquo;s
      appearance is peculiar, his face especially, and I am sure it was himself.
      What I want to find out is, who was his companion?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I hardly see what, interest that can be to you,&rsquo; observed George
      suspiciously, &lsquo;since you only know him&mdash;by sight!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The lady interested me. I was wondering if it could be your charming
      cousin.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George started as if he had been shot.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My Cousin Alma! Impossible! Surely you don&rsquo;t know what you are saying!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh yes, I do. Tell me, what is your cousin like?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      After some slight further urging, George described Alma&rsquo;s personal
      appearance as closely as possible. Mrs. Montmorency listened quietly,
      taking note of all the details of the description. Then she tapped George
      with her fan, and laughed outright.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then I was right after all!&rsquo; she cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It was Miss Alma Craik&mdash;that&rsquo;s her name, isn&rsquo;t it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes; but, good heavens, it is simply impossible! Alma in company with
      that scoundrel, over there in France? You must be mistaken!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      But Mrs. Montmorency was quite certain that she had made no mistake in the
      matter. In her turn she described Alma&rsquo;s appearance so minutely, so
      cleverly, that her companion became lost in astonished belief. When the
      act drop was rung up, he sat staring like one bewitched, seeing nothing,
      hearing nothing, but gazing wildly at Mrs. Montmorency.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly he rose to go.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t go yet,&rsquo; whispered the lady.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I must&mdash;I can&rsquo;t stay!&rsquo; he replied. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll find out from my cousin
      herself if what you have told me is true.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;<i>Apres?</i>&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;<i>Après!</i>&rsquo; echoed the young man, looking-livid. &lsquo;Why, <i>après</i>,
      I&rsquo;ll have it out with the man!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Montmorency put her gloved hand upon his arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t do anything rash, <i>mon cher,</i>&rsquo; she said. &lsquo;I think you told me
      that you loved your cousin, and that you would give a thousand pounds to
      get her away from your rival?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A thousand! twenty thousand! anything!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Suppose I could help you?&rsquo; said Mrs. Montmorency, smiling wickedly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Can you? will you? But how!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You must give me time to think it over. Find out, in the first place, if
      what I suspect is true, and then come and tell me all about it!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik promised, and hurriedly left the theatre, without even
      waiting to say farewell, or make any apologies, to Miss Destrange. He was
      determined to call upon his cousin without a moment&rsquo;s delay, and get, if
      possible, to the bottom of the mystery of her unaccountable appearance,
      accompanied by Bradley, at the Rouen railway station.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0005" id="link2HCH0005"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XV.&mdash;THE COUSINS.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      Madam, our house&rsquo;s honour is in question!
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      I prithee, when you play at wantonness,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Remember that our blood flows clean and pure,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      In one unbroken and unmuddied line,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      From crystal sources. I&rsquo;m your champion,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Madam, against yourself!&mdash;<i>The Will and the Way</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">G</span>eorge Craik was
      not the man to let the grass grow under his feet when he was moving with
      set purpose to any object.
    </p>
    <p>
      As we have already hinted, he possessed a certain bull-dog tenacity, very
      dangerous to his opponents. And now all the suspicions of a nature
      naturally suspicious, all the spitefulness of a disposition naturally
      spiteful, being fully and unexpectedly aroused, his furious instinct urged
      him to seek, without a moment&rsquo;s breathing-time, the presence of his
      refractory cousin.
    </p>
    <p>
      Coupled with his jealous excitement was a lofty moral indignation.
    </p>
    <p>
      The family credit was at stake&mdash;so at least he assured himself&mdash;and
      he had a perfect right to demand an explanation. Had he reflected a
      little, he might have known that Alma was the last person in the world to
      give any explanation whatever if peremptorily demanded, or to admit her
      cousin&rsquo;s right to demand it; her spirit was stubborn as his own, and her
      attitude of intellectual superiority was, he should have known by old
      experience, quite invincible.
    </p>
    <p>
      Quitting the theatre, he leapt into a hansom, and was driven direct to
      Alma&rsquo;s rooms. It was by this time about five in the afternoon, and he made
      certain of finding his cousin at home.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was mistaken. Miss Craik was out, and had been out the greater part of
      the day.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do you know where I can find her?&rsquo; he asked of the domestic, a smart
      servant maid.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know, sir,&rsquo; was the reply. &lsquo;She went out in the morning with Mr.
      Bradley, and has not been home to lunch.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Does she dine at home?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sir&mdash;at seven.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then I will wait for her.&rsquo; And so saying he walked into the drawing-room
      and sat down.
    </p>
    <p>
      He had cooled a little by this time, and before Alma made her appearance
      he had time to cool a good deal more. Fidgetting impatiently in his chair,
      he began to ask himself how he could best approach the subject on which he
      had come. He regretted now that he had not called for his father and
      brought him with him; that, no doubt, would have been the most diplomatic
      course to adopt. The more he thought over the information he had received,
      the more he questioned its authenticity; and if, after all, the actress
      had made a mistake, as he began to suspect and fear, what a fool he would
      be made to look in his cousin&rsquo;s eyes! The prospect of being made to appear
      absurd sent a thrill of horror through his blood; for this young person,
      as has already been seen, dreaded, above all things in the world, the
      shaft of ridicule.
    </p>
    <p>
      Time slipped by, and George Craik grew more and more uneasy. At last seven
      o&rsquo;clock struck, and Alma had not appeared.
    </p>
    <p>
      Growling to himself like an irritable dog, the young man rose and touched
      the electric bell.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mv cousin is very late,&rsquo; he said to the servant when she appeared.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sir; she is very uncertain.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It is seven o&rsquo;clock. You said she dined at seven.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sir. But sometimes she does not return to dinner, If she is not here
      at the hour we don&rsquo;t expect her.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik uttered an angry exclamation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where the deuce can she be?&rsquo; he cried, scowling ominously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t say, sir,&rsquo; returned the servant smiling. &lsquo;Miss Craik is most
      uncertain, as I told you. She may be dining out&mdash;with Mr. Bradley.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The young man seized his hat, and began striding up and down the room.
      Then he stopped, and seeing a curious smile still lingering on the
      servant&rsquo;s face, said sharply:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What are you laughing at? This is no laughing matter. I tell you I must
      see my cousin!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m very sorry, sir, but&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George moved towards the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll go and look for her,&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;If she returns before I find her,
      tell her I&rsquo;ll come the first thing in the morning.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      And, fuming savagely, he left the house. His temper, never very amiable,
      was now aroused to the extreme point of irritation, and the servant&rsquo;s
      suggestion that Alma might at that very moment be in his rival&rsquo;s company
      roused in him a certain frenzy. It was scandalous; it was insufferable. If
      he could not have it out that night with her, he would seek the clergyman,
      and force him to some sort of an avowal. Bent on that purpose, he hurried
      away towards Bradley&rsquo;s house.
    </p>
    <p>
      He passed on foot round Regent&rsquo;s Park, and came to the neighbourhood of
      the New Church and the adjoining house where Bradley dwelt. It was quite
      dark now, and the outskirts of the park were quite deserted. As he
      approached the house he saw the street-door standing open, and heard the
      sound of voices. He pricked up his ears and drew back into the shadow.
    </p>
    <p>
      A light silvery laugh rose upon the air, followed by the low, deep tones
      of a man&rsquo;s voice. Then the door was closed, and two ligures stepped out
      into the road, crossing to the opposite side, under the shadow of the
      trees.
    </p>
    <p>
      They passed across the lamplight on the other side of the way, and he
      recognised his cousin&rsquo;s figure, arm-in-arm with that of the clergyman.
      They passed on, laughing and talking merrily together.
    </p>
    <p>
      Keeping them well at a distance, he quietly followed.
    </p>
    <p>
      They passed round the park, following the road by which he himself had
      come. Happy and unsuspicious, they continued to talk as they went; and
      though he was not near enough to follow their conversation, he heard
      enough to show him that they were on the tenderest and most loving terms.
    </p>
    <p>
      More than once he felt inclined to stride forward, confront them, and have
      it out with his rival; but, his courage failing him, he continued to
      follow like a spy. At last they reached the quiet street where Alma dwelt,
      and paused on the doorstep of her house.
    </p>
    <p>
      He drew back, waited, and listened.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Will you not come in?&rsquo; he heard his cousin say.
    </p>
    <p>
      He could not hear the reply, but it was accompanied by a kiss and an
      embrace, which made the jealous blood boil and burn along his veins.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good-night, dearest!&rsquo; said Alma.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good night, my darling!&rsquo; answered the deep voice of the clergyman.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then the two seemed to embrace and kiss again, and the next moment the
      house door opened and closed.
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik stepped forward, and stood waiting on the pavement for
      Bradley to pass, right under the light of a street lamp. Almost
      immediately Bradley came up quietly, and they were face to face.
    </p>
    <p>
      The clergyman started, and at first George Craik thought that he was
      recognised; but the next moment Bradley passed by, without any sign of
      recognition, and before the other could make up his mind what to do, he
      was out of sight.
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik looked at his watch; it was still early, and he determined at
      once to interview his cousin. He knocked at the door and asked for her;
      she heard his voice and came out into the lobby, charmingly attired in an
      evening dress of the &lsquo;crushed strawberry&rsquo; tint, so much favoured by ladies
      of æsthetic leaning. Never had she looked more bright and beautiful. Her
      cheeks were flushed, her eyes sparkling, and she looked radiantly happy.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is it you, George?&rsquo; she cried. &lsquo;What brings you so late? I hope no one is
      ill. My uncle&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;O, <i>he&rsquo;s</i> all right!&rsquo; answered George, entering the drawing-room.
      &lsquo;No one is ill, or dead, or that kind of thing; so make your mind easy.
      Besides, it&rsquo;s only nine o&rsquo;clock, and you don&rsquo;t call <i>that</i> late, do
      you?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      His manner was peculiar, and she noticed that he hardly looked her in the
      face. Closing the room door, she stood facing him on the hearthrug, and by
      his side she looked a queen. The miserable young man was immediately
      submerged in the sense of inferiority irksome to him, and he looked at
      once cowed and savage.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, George, what is it?&rsquo; continued Alma. &lsquo;I suppose it&rsquo;s some new
      trouble about yourself. Uncle told me the other day you were rather
      worried about money, and I offered to help you out of it if I could.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George threw himself on a sofa and leant forward, sucking the end of his
      cane.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It isn&rsquo;t that,&rsquo; he replied. &lsquo;If it were, you know I shouldn&rsquo;t come to
      you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why not?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Because I have no right, Alma; you have never given me any right. I hope
      you don&rsquo;t think me mean enough to sponge upon you because you happen, to
      be my cousin, and much richer than I am! But I <i>am</i> your cousin,
      after all, and I think I have a right to protect you, when I see you
      likely to get into trouble.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      This was quite a magnificent speech for George Craik; for anger and moral
      indignation had made him eloquent. Alma looked down upon him in all the
      pleasurable pride of her beauty, half smiling; for to her poor George was
      always a small boy, whose attempts to lecture her were absurd. Her arms
      and neck were bare, there were jewels on her neck and heaving bosom, her
      complexion was dazzlingly clear and bright, and altogether she looked
      superb. There was a large mirror opposite to her, covering half the side
      of the room; and within it another Alma, her counterpart, shone dimly in
      the faint pink light of the lamps, with their rose-coloured shades.
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik was obtuse in some respects, but he did not fail to notice
      that his cousin was unusually resplendent. She had never been extravagant
      in her toilette, and he had seldom seen her in such bright colours as on
      the present occasion. Everything about her betokened an abundant
      happiness, which she could scarcely conceal.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What do you mean by getting into trouble?&rsquo; she inquired carelessly.
      &lsquo;Surely I am old enough to take care of myself.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t think you are,&rsquo; he answered. &lsquo;At any rate, people are talking
      about you, and&mdash;and I don&rsquo;t like it!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Alma shrugged her white shoulders.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why shouldn&rsquo;t people talk, if it pleases them? But what are they saying?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The ice was broken, and now was the time for George to take the plunge. He
      hesitated seriously for a moment, and then proceeded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;They are saying scandalous things, and I think you ought to know.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;About <i>me</i>, George?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;About you and that man Bradley.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Indeed!&rsquo; exclaimed Alma, and she laughed quite joyously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s no laughing matter,&rsquo; cried Craik angrily. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s a matter that
      concerns our family, and our family honour. I tell you they couple your
      name with his in a way that makes a fellow shudder. That is why I came
      here to remonstrate with you. I heard this afternoon that you and this man
      were seen in Normandy together, at a time when everybody supposed you to
      be here in London.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Alma started and flushed crimson. Was her secret discovered? For her own
      part, she did not much care; indeed, she would have rejoiced greatly to
      publish her great happiness to all the world; but she respected Bradley&rsquo;s
      wishes, and was resolute in keeping silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      The young man rose to his feet, and continued eagerly:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Let me tell you, Alma, that I don&rsquo;t believe a word of it. I know you are
      indiscreet, of course; but I am sure you would never compromise yourself
      or us in any way. But it&rsquo;s all over the place that you were seen together
      over at Rouen, and I want you to give me the authority to say it&rsquo;s an
      infernal lie!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Alma was rather disconcerted. She was at a loss how to reply. But she was
      so secure in her own sense of happy safety, that she was more amused than
      annoyed by her cousin&rsquo;s indignation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Suppose it were the truth. George? Where would be the harm?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good God! you don&rsquo;t mean to tell me it <i>is</i> true!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Perhaps not,&rsquo; was the quiet reply. &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t mean to answer such
      accusations, one way or the other.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik went livid.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But you don&rsquo;t deny it!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Certainly not. Let people talk what nonsense they please; it is quite
      indifferent to me.&rsquo; &lsquo;Indifferent!&rsquo; echoed George Craik. &lsquo;Do you know your
      character is at stake? Do you know they say that you are this man&rsquo;s
      mistress?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Even yet, Alma betrayed less anger and astonishment than one might have
      thought possible; for, though the infamous charge shocked her, she was too
      confident in her own security, in the knowledge of her happy secret, which
      she could at any moment publish to the world, to be greatly or deeply
      moved. But if the matter of her cousin&rsquo;s discourse failed to disconcert
      her, its manner irritated her not a little. She made an eager movement
      towards the door as if to leave the room; but, wheeling, round suddenly,
      she raked him from head to foot with a broadside from her scornful eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And I suppose <i>you</i> are quite ready to accept such a calumny!&rsquo; she
      cried scornfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Nothing of the sort,&rsquo; returned George. &lsquo;I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;d never go as far as
      that!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She gave a gesture of supreme disdain, and repeated the sense word for
      word with contemptuous emphasis.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;re sure I&rsquo;d never go as far as that! How good and kind of you to have
      so much faith in me! Do you know that every syllable you utter to me is an
      insult and an outrage, and that if Mr. Bradley heard you talk as you have
      done, he would give you the whipping you so richly deserve!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Here George Craik&rsquo;s self-control gave way; his face grew black as thunder,
      and clenching his fist, he gave vent to an angry oath.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;D&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; him! I should like to see him try it on. But I see
      what it is. He has dragged you down to his level at last, the infernal
      atheist! He thinks nothing sacred, and his New Church, as he calls it, is
      as foul as himself. O, <i>I</i> know! He preaches that marriage isn&rsquo;t a
      sacrament at all, but only a contract to be broken by the will of either
      party; and as you agree with him in everything, I suppose you agree with
      him in <i>that</i>, and are his mistress after all!&rsquo; &lsquo;That is enough!&rsquo;
      exclaimed Alma, who was now pale as death. &lsquo;Leave this place at once, and
      never let me see your face again.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I won&rsquo;t go till I have spoken my mind; and don&rsquo;t make any mistake; I
      shall speak it to him as well as to you!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If you have any sense left, you will do nothing of the kind.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Won&rsquo;t I? Wait and see!&rsquo; returned George, perfectly beside himself with
      rage. &lsquo;As for you, I wonder you have the courage to look me in the face. I
      followed you both to-night, and watched you; I saw you embracing and
      kissing, and it turned me sick with shame. There, the secret&rsquo;s out! I
      shall speak to my father, and see what <i>he</i> has to say about your
      goings on.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      As he spoke, Alma approached him and looked him steadily in the face. She
      was still ghastly pale, and her voice trembled as she spoke, but her
      entire manner expressed, not fear, but lofty indignation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It is like you to play the spy! It is just what I should have expected!
      Well, I hope you are satisfied. I love Mr. Bradley; I have loved him since
      the day we first met. Will you go now?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      George Craik seized his hat and stick, and crossed to the door, where he
      turned.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I will take care all the world knows of your shameless conduct!&rsquo; he
      cried. &lsquo;You have brought disgrace upon us all. As for this man, he shall
      be exposed; he shall, by&mdash;! He is a scoundrel not lit to live!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Without replying, Alma pointed to the door; and, after one last look of
      concentrated rage, George Craik rushed from the house. She heard the outer
      door close behind him, but still stood like marble, holding her hand upon
      her heart. Then, with a low cry, she sank shuddering into a chair, and
      covered her face with her hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      The scene which we have described had tortured her delicate spirit more
      than she at first knew; and her cousin&rsquo;s bitter taunts and reproaches,
      though they missed their mark at first, had struck home in the end. She
      was a woman of infinite sensitiveness, exceeding sweetness of disposition;
      and she could not bear harsh words, even from one she cordially despised.
      Above all, she shrank, like all good women, even the most intellectual,
      before the evil judgment of the world. Could it be true, as George Craik
      had said, that people were connecting her name infamously with that of
      Bradley? If so, then surely it was time to let all the world know her
      happiness.
    </p>
    <p>
      She drew forth from her bosom a photographic miniature of Bradley, set in
      a golden locket. For a long time she looked at it intently, through a mist
      of loving tears. Then she kissed it fondly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He loves me!&rsquo; she murmured to herself. &lsquo;I will tell him what they are
      saying, and then he will know that it is time to throw away all disguise.
      Ah! how proud I shall be when I can stand by his side, holding his hand,
      and say &ldquo;This is my husband!&rdquo;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
